HEADWORD: Multitudinous
<hw>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Consisting of a multitude; manifold in number or condition; <as>as,
<ex>multitudinous</ex> waves</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>multitudinous</xex> seas.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A renewed jingling of <qex>multitudinous</qex> chains.</q>
<rj><qau>G. Kennan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a multitude.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>multitudinous</xex> tongue.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Mul`ti*tu"di*nous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

